                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" id="avoirdupois_sng_1" hclass="sense" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">the system of weights based on a pound of 16 <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/ounce#ounce_sng_1" title="ounces definition"><span class="ndv">ounces</span></a>, widely used in English-speaking countries</span></span><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="avoirdupois_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">Middle English (denoting merchandise sold by weight): from Old French <span class="ei">aveir de peis</span> ‘goods of weight’, from <span class="ei">aveir</span> ‘to have’ (infinitive used as a noun, from Latin <span class="ei">habere</span>) + <span class="ei">peis</span> ‘weight’ from an alteration of Latin <span class="ei">pensum</span> ‘weight’, from the verb <span class="ei">pendere</span> ‘weigh’.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
